# Rules for Jekyll Project

## Project Overview
- **Framework**: Jekyll static site generator
- **Language**: Ukrainian (all content, UI text)
- **Style**: Business/Professional
- **Purpose**: Software products advertisement and promotion
- **Repository**: GitHub
- **Deployment**: AWS S3 + CloudFront CDN with SSL
- **CI/CD**: GitHub Actions workflows
- **Environments**: Development (dev) and Production (prod)

## Language Requirements
- Code comments in English
- Variable/function names in English (standard practice)

## Project Structure

```
├── _config.yml          # Site configuration
├── _config_dev.yml      # Dev environment overrides
├── _data/               # Data files (navigation, features, etc.)
├── _includes/           # Reusable components
├── _layouts/            # Page templates
├── _products/           # Product collection
├── _sass/               # SCSS partials
├── assets/              # Static files (CSS, JS, images)
├── .github/workflows/   # CI/CD configuration
└── docs/                # Documentation
```

## Business Style Guidelines
- Professional, clean, modern design
- Focus on clarity and conversion
- Responsive design (mobile-first approach)
- Fast loading times (optimize images, minify assets)
- Accessible design (WCAG 2.1 AA compliance)
- Clear call-to-action buttons
- Professional typography

## Code Style
- Semantic HTML5
- BEM methodology for CSS class naming
- SCSS/Sass for stylesheets
- Vanilla JS (minimal, modular)
- Consistent indentation: 2 spaces (YAML), 2-4 spaces (HTML/CSS/JS)

## File Organization
- Keep configuration files at root level
- Organize assets logically (images, CSS, JS)
- Use includes for reusable components
- Separate concerns (layout, content, styling)
- Document custom configurations

## Security & Performance
- Use environment variables for sensitive data
- Optimize images (WebP format where possible)
- Minify CSS and JavaScript in production
- Enable CloudFront compression
- Use HTTPS everywhere (SSL/TLS)
- Implement proper caching headers

